The Eiffel Tower is an iconic wrought-iron lattice tower located on the Champ de Mars in Paris, France. It is named after the engineer Gustave Eiffel, whose company designed and built the structure. The tower was constructed between 1887 and 1889 as the entrance arch for the 1889 World's Fair, held to celebrate the 100th anniversary of the French Revolution. Standing approximately 324 meters (1,063 feet) tall, it was the world's tallest man-made structure until the completion of the Chrysler Building in New York City in 1930.

The Eiffel Tower is one of the most recognizable structures in the world and a global cultural icon of France. It is visited by millions of tourists each year and offers panoramic views of Paris from its various observation decks on different levels. The tower's design and construction were initially met with criticism from some Parisians, but it has since become a beloved landmark celebrated for its architectural and engineering significance.

The Eiffel Tower was constructed between 1887 and 1889. It was completed in time to serve as the entrance arch for the 1889 World's Fair (Exposition Universelle), which was held in Paris to commemorate the 100th anniversary of the French Revolution. Construction of the tower began on January 28, 1887, and it was officially completed on March 31, 1889.
